CS0168.shortDescription: La variable está declarada pero nunca se usa

S1066.fullDescription: Nested code - blocks of code inside blocks of code - is eventually necessary, but increases complexity. This is why keeping the code as flat as possible, by avoiding unnecessary nesting, is considered a good practice.

S108.shortDescription: Nested blocks of code should not be left empty
S108.fullDescription: An empty code block is confusing. It will require some effort from maintainers to determine if it is intentional or indicates the implementation is incomplete.

S1104.shortDescription: Fields should not have public accessibility
S1104.fullDescription: Public fields in public classes do not respect the encapsulation principle and have three main disadvantages:

S1117.shortDescription: Local variables should not shadow class fields or properties
S1117.fullDescription: Shadowing occurs when a local variable has the same name as a variable, field, or property in an outer scope.

S1118.shortDescription: Utility classes should not have public constructors
S1118.fullDescription: Whenever there are portions of code that are duplicated and do not depend on the state of their container class, they can be centralized inside a "utility class". A utility class is a class that only has static members, hence it should not be instantiated.

S1144.shortDescription: Unused private types or members should be removed
S1144.fullDescription: This rule raises an issue when a private/internal type or member is never referenced in the code.

S1155.shortDescription: "Any()" should be used to test for emptiness
S1155.fullDescription: When you call Any(), it clearly communicates the code’s intention, which is to check if the collection is empty. Using Count() == 0 for this purpose is less direct and makes the code slightly more complex. However, there are some cases where special attention should be paid:

S1186.fullDescription: An empty method is generally considered bad practice and can lead to confusion, readability, and maintenance issues. Empty methods bring no functionality and are misleading to others as they might think the method implementation fulfills a specific and identified requirement.

S125.shortDescription: Sections of code should not be commented out
S125.fullDescription: Commented-out code distracts the focus from the actual executed code. It creates a noise that increases maintenance code. And because it is never executed, it quickly becomes out of date and invalid.

S2219.shortDescription: Runtime type checking should be simplified
S2219.fullDescription: To check the type of an object there are several options:

S2223.shortDescription: Non-constant static fields should not be visible
S2223.fullDescription: Unlike instance fields, which can only be accessed by code having a hold on the instance, static fields can be accessed by any code having visibility of the field and its type.

S2245.shortDescription: Using pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) is security-sensitive

S2292.fullDescription: Trivial properties, which include no logic but setting and getting a backing field should be converted to auto-implemented properties, yielding cleaner and more readable code.

S2696.shortDescription: Instance members should not write to "static" fields
S2696.fullDescription: This rule raises an issue each time a static field is updated from a non-static method or property.

S2971.fullDescription: In the interests of readability, code that can be simplified should be simplified. To that end, there are several ways IEnumerable language integrated queries (LINQ) can be simplified. This not only improves readabilty but can also lead to improved performance.

S3010.shortDescription: Static fields should not be updated in constructors
S3010.fullDescription: Assigning a value to a static field in a constructor could cause unreliable behavior at runtime since it will change the value for all instances of the class.

S927.shortDescription: Parameter names should match base declaration and other partial definitions
S927.fullDescription: Parameters are part of the method signature and its identity.
